The following describes risks driven by changes in regulation:

Risk driver: General environmental regulations including planning;
Description: Aetna considers itself indirectly exposed to regulatory risks related to greenhouse gas emissions As a US-based insurance benefits corporation, Aetna does not produce products or services leading directly to the emissions of substantial amounts of greenhouse gases or other pollutants Aetna considers the impact to this driver to be from additional costs associated with regulatory compliance; Potential impact: Increased operational cost;
Time-frame: >6 years;
Direct/Indirect: Indirect (supply chain);
Likeli-hood: About as likely as not;
Magnitude of impact: Low;
Estimated financial implications: Unknown Aetna operations are housed predominately in leased locations with minimal fuel burning equipment on-site Any regulatory risk is expected to be generated by Aetna's purchase of electricity or fuels  As the majority of Aetna leases include electricity and other utilities in the lease rate, the amount Aetna pays may increase, although by how much is uncertain
Management method: Unknown The majority of Aetna leases are multi-year If regulations were to drive electrical and fuel costs higher, it is expected that these increased costs would be passed on to Aetna If that were the case then Aetna could pursue separate metering allowing Aetna the opportunity to handle the costs directly and then to implement measures to lower electricity and fuel costs to reap any savings
Cost of mgt: Unknown

The following describes risks driven by change in physical climate parameters:
Risk driver: Change in temperature extremes;
Description: Aetna considers itself indirectly exposed to physical risks related to physical climate parameters - either extreme heat or cold; Risk driver: Change in temperature extremes;
Description: Aetna considers itself indirectly exposed to physical risks related to physical climate parameters - either extreme heat or cold;Potential impact: Increased operational cost;
Time frame: >6 years;
Direct/Indirect: Indirect (Supply chain);
Likeli-hood: About as likely as not;	
Magnitude of impact: Low;	
Estimated financial implications: Unknown Aetna operations are housed predominately in leased locations At this point it is unclear whether Aetna would need to relocate offices based upon temperature extremes, whether mitigating methods would or would not be available, or what the costs associated with these would be Aetna has a Business Continuity Unit which creates and incorporates scenarios addressing situations that would impact its operations;	
Mgt method: Aetna constantly evaluates its business operations and demands tailoring its real estate requirements to meet these needs Several options are available whether it be relocation, reduction (or increase) in real estate and facility needs, increasing telecommuting options, etc Aetna's Business Continuity Department addresses situations such as that would impact its operations incorporating various strategies such as re-direction of operations, identifying a need for  alternative locations, etc
Cost of mgt: The future costs associated with this management method are expected to be similar if not identical to current expenditures

